'''Dealey Decherd Herndon''' (born January 10, 1947) is a [[historic preservation|historic preservationist]] in [[Texas]]. She was inducted into the [[Texas Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cemetery.state.tx.us/pub/user_form.asp?pers_id=11421 |title=Dealey Decherd Herndon |publisher=Texas State Cemetery}}</ref><ref name=twu/>

The daughter of H. Benjamin Decherd Jr., she was born '''Dealey Decherd'''. Her brother [[Robert Decherd|Robert]] is a retired media business owner.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.dallasnews.com/news/news/2013/09/07/robert-w.-decherd-leaves-four-decade-legacy-of-newspaper-service |title= Robert W. Decherd leaves four-decade legacy of newspaper service |newspaper= Dallas News |date= September 7, 2013}}</ref> Herndon is a graduate of the [[University of Texas]].<ref name=utextas/>

She was executive director of the [[Texas State Preservation Board]] from 1991 to 1995. From 1995 to 2006, she was president of the project management and construction management firm Herndon, Stauch & Associates which oversaw s number of restoration projects including the [[George W. Bush Childhood Home]] and the [[Caldwell County Courthouse (Texas)|Caldwell County Historic Courthouse]].<ref name=utextas>{{cite web |url=http://alcalde.texasexes.org/2014/07/announcing-the-2014-distinguished-alumni/ |title= Announcing the 2014 Distinguished Alumni |work=Alcade |publisher=University of Texas |date=July 14, 2014}}</ref> She was project coordinator for the [[Bullock Texas State History Museum|Texas State History Museum]].<ref name=twu>{{cite web |url= http://www.twu.edu/twhf/tw-herndon.asp |title= Herndon, Dealey Decherd |work= Texas Women's Hall of Fame |publisher= Texas Woman's University |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130208092950/http://www.twu.edu/twhf/tw-herndon.asp |archivedate= 2013-02-08 |df=  }}</ref> She was awarded the Texas Medal of Arts in 2003. She served as president of the Heritage Society of Austin and of the Texas State History Museum Foundation. Herndon was also president of the board of directors of the Friends of the Governor’s Mansion and chair of the board of trustees for [[St. Edward's University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://texasmedalofarts.org/honorees/dealy-herndon/ |title=Dealy Herndon |work=Honorees, Texas Medal of Arts}}</ref> She has served on the board of directors of [[A. H. Belo]] Corporation since 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ahbelo.com/about/herndon.x2 |title=Dealey D. Herndon |publisher=A. H. Belo Corporation}}</ref>

