[[File:Painted 1897 loving cup wiki.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Porcelain loving cup made for Queen Victoria's 1897 Diamond Jubilee.]]
A '''loving cup''' is a shared drinking container traditionally used at weddings and banquets. It usually has two handles and is often made of silver. Loving cups are often given as [[trophy|trophies]] to winners of games or other competitions.<ref> {{cite encyclopedia | title = Loving cup | encyclopedia = [[Encyclopædia Britannica]] online | accessdate = 2009-03-23 | url = http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/349630/loving-cup }} </ref><ref>[http://www.lambawards.com Trophy Loving Cup]</ref><ref>[https://www.martinawards.com/custom-awards/trophy-cups/ Trophy Loving Cup examples]</ref> They can be found in several European cultures, including the Celtic ''[[quaich]]'' and the French ''coupe de mariage''.<ref> {{cite web | url = http://www.celebrateintimateweddings.com/lovingcup.html | accessdate = 2009-03-23 | title = Loving Cup Ceremony | work = CelebrateIntimateWeddings.com }} </ref>
{{anchor|bratina}} The Russian ''[[wikt:братина|bratina]]'' ("fraternity cup" or "brotherhood cup") is a wine bowl also used for banquets. It is considered the "Russian version of the loving cup".<ref>{{cite book|author=Peter Andrews|title=The Rulers of Russia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xBMsAQAAMAAJ|year=1983|publisher=Stonehenge|isbn=978-0-86706-051-5|page=50|quote= Another exceptional vessel was the bratina. This Russian version of the loving cup, or toasting bowl, was passed from person to person, uniting all who drank from it in etemal brotherhood.}}</ref> It is often without handles. (See: {{Commons category-inline|bratina}})
