'''Paula Hays Harper''' (born Paula Fish: November 17, 1930 &ndash; June 3, 2012<ref name="nytobit" />) was an American art historian, credited as "one of the first art historians to bring a feminist perspective to the study of painting and sculpture". She co-authored a biography on the French impressionist [[Camille Pissarro]] and was a well-known contemporary art critic.

== Life and work ==
Paula Fish was an only child, born in Scituate, [[Massachusetts]], who grew up in Philadelphia. In her 20s she moved to New York City, where she was a dancer with the modern dance company [[Munt-Brooks]] (later known as "[[Alfred Brooks (dancer)|The Changing Scene]]" dance).<ref name=":0" /> After a dance-related injury she decided to study art history at [[Hunter College]] in New York and earned her bachelor's and master's degree. In 1976 she earned her PhD in art history from [[Stanford University]].<ref name=":0" /> Harper was married twice and never had children; she preferred using her two married names "Hays Harper" because of a dislike of her maiden name.<ref name="nytobit" /><ref name=":0" />

Harper was "instrumental" in the establishment of the [[Feminist Art Program]] at the [[California Institute of the Arts]] in the early 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paula Harper Memorial|last=Shabaka|first=Onajide|date=12 August 2012|publisher=[[Examiner.com]] (Miami)}}</ref> Harper is credited with conceiving [[Womanhouse]], a 1972 art installation<ref>{{cite book|last=Phelan|first=Peggy|title=Live Art in LA: Performance in Southern California, 1970-1983|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DaoZSpldJZ8C&pg=PA38|year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415684224|page=38}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lib.stanford.edu/women-art-revolution/transcript-interview-miriam-schapiro-1990|title=Transcript of Interview with Miriam Schapiro 1990 |last=Hershman|first=Lynn|date=30 May 1990|work=[[Stanford University]]|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref> and "one of the biggest and most celebrated exhibitions of art by and about women ever assembled".<ref name="nytobit" />

In 1981 Paula Hays Harper collaborated with Ralph E. Shikes on a comprehensive biography of the 19th-century French Impressionist Camille Pissarro.<ref name=":0" />

She taught at the [[University of Miami]] from 1983 until her retirement in 2011.<ref name="nytobit">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/26/arts/design/paula-hays-harper-feminist-art-historian-dies-at-81.html?_r=0|title=Paula Hays Harper, Art Historian, Is Dead at 81|last=Grady|first=Denise|date=25 June 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref> She helped shape the Miami art scene and was a regular contributor and art critic in [[Art in America]] magazine and [[The Miami News]].<ref name=":0" />

Harper died at age 81 in Miami, Florida, from complications of a rare skin cancer.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url = http://alumni.stanford.edu/get/page/magazine/article/?article_id=55999|title = Feminist Art Historian|date = September–October 2012|accessdate = May 28, 2014|website = Stanford Alumni Magazine|publisher = Stanford University|last = Muller Mitchell|first = Julie}}</ref>

